Gautam Goel, Sujay Desai
Developing Positional Proles for
Player Scouting
Research Question
Suppose you are a club looking to sign a new player. Some characteristics you might consider…
● Player’s ability to t into your style of play
● Player’s mesh with the team culture and dynamic
● Player’s ability to exceed productivity of previous player
More formally…
How can we build a player prole to help determine t and aid with scouting?
Approach…
Build a proof-of-concept charting tool, comparing performance proles of two La Liga players
using key game metrics, that can then be implemented on a larger-scale
Player A
*Utilized passing, dribbling, and shot data for a La Liga team (2018-2019 season) from the Open Data repository on GitHub
Player B
Observations Insights
During open play (dribbling and passing), Player B appears to
prefer the right side of the eld whereas Player A plays more
centrally.
If you are looking for a striker/winger, Player B is preferable as
his prole ts that mold. Whereas Player A is more of a central
midelder.
Player A attempts more shots and is more successful from
distance than Player B, who seems hesitant to shoot from
outside the box.
If you are looking for a pure striker, Player B is the best choice
as he is lethal in the box. If you are looking for more of an
attacking midelder, Player A is preferable as he can distribute
the ball or attack the defense.
Both players generally score most of their goals from the center
of the pitch. Player B takes shots from both sides of the goal,
but is generally only successful from the center.
If you are looking for players who can attack down the middle,
either player is a good option, but if you prefer players
attacking from the side, Player A has the slight edge.
Assumptions:
● Passing, dribbling, and shot data are indicators of player performance and style of play
● Positional prole concept can be easily extended to data from other leagues, teams, and players
*Player A: Lionel Messi, Player B: Luis Suárez
Future Analysis
1. Maximize player performance
a. Analyze player performance over multiple seasons
b. Are there variances in passing, dribbling, and shooting maps?
c. Are the variances due to player improvement or team’s style of play?
2. Develop appropriate tactics
a. Analyze opposing players proles prior to a match
b. Understand opposing players style of play and team’s identity
c. Compare to your own team to determine possible weaknesses
3. Optimize team performance
a. Determine where on the pitch each player contributes most
b. Adjust tactics/formations to put players in a position to succeed
c. Develop drills to improve weaknesses
*Code on Github: https://github.com/gautam-goel/Sounders-Data-Competition
